  "market_context": "Clear downtrend on GBPUSD 4H chart; recent bearish impulsive move from ~1.27403 to ~1.26214. Analyst identifies premium zone above 50% Fib (1.26809) for short entries, with supporting FVG and OB in that zone.",
  "key_observation": "Price entered the premium zone (above 50% Fib retracement of the latest bearish impulse), where a marked FVG and OB formed; subsequent 1H liquidity sweep above equal highs confirmed a fakeout, followed by CHoCH signaling continuation of downtrend.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the 4H GBPUSD chart, analyst applied Fibonacci retracement to the latest bearish impulsive wave (low at 1.26214, high at 1.27403), identifying 50% level at 1.26809 and defining premium zone above it.",
    "Step 2: Analyst marked a small FVG and its preceding candle as an Order Block (OB) within the premium zone (~1.2695–1.2705), designating this as the optimal trading area for shorts.",
    "Step 3: Zoomed into 1H chart to monitor price action inside the premium zone; identified equal highs, then a liquidity sweep above them, interpreted as a fakeout to collect SSL.",
    "Step 4: Observed a Change of Character (CHoCH) on 1H after the sweep—price broke below the prior swing low, confirming bearish structure continuation within the premium zone.",
    "Step 5: Zoomed to 15M chart to refine entry; identified an unmitigated FVG near the swing high (~1.26850–1.26955), placed short entry just below it with stop above the swing high.",
    "Step 6: Set initial take profit at the nearest swing low and applied trailing stop technique: repositioning stop above prior swing high each time price broke a new swing low."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade entered short on 15M FVG with stop above swing high; trailing stop used to lock in profits as price moved lower—analyst described the technique but did not state final P/L or closure time.",
  "lessons": "High-probability shorts occur when price enters premium zone in a downtrend, combines with liquidity sweep + CHoCH on LTF, and confirms with FVG/OB on HTF; trailing stops protect gains during strong impulses.",
